    "content": "## Theorem: mathd_numbertheory_277\n\nTheorem: mathd_numbertheory_277\nVariables: m, n (integer)\nGiven: h₀ : nat.gcd m n = 6\nGiven: h₁ : nat.lcm m n = 126\nProve: 60 ≤ m + n\n\nGoal: 60 ≤ m + n\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"Write m and n as 6a and 6b with gcd(a,b)=1; then the lcm condition forces ab=21, so the only possible coprime factor pairs give the smallest sum m+n = 60.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Use the gcd condition to factor out 6 from m and n.\",\n    \"Translate the lcm condition into a relation between the reduced factors.\",\n    \"Use coprimality to identify the possible factor pairs of 21.\",\n    \"Compute the corresponding minimum of m+n and conclude it is at least 60.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"There exist integers a and b such that m = 6a, n = 6b, and gcd(a,b) = 1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since gcd(m,n)=6, both m and n are divisible by 6. Writing m=6a and n=6b, dividing out the common gcd shows that a and b must be coprime.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of gcd\",\n        \"divisibility from gcd\",\n        \"basic factorization by common divisor\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"lcm(m,n) = 36ab.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"For m=6a and n=6b with gcd(a,b)=1, we have gcd(6a,6b)=6 and hence lcm(6a,6b) = |(6a)(6b)| / gcd(6a,6b) = 36ab, using the standard gcd-lcm product formula.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"gcd-lcm product formula\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"ab = 21.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By the hypothesis lcm(m,n)=126 and the previous step, 36ab=126. Dividing by 18 gives 2ab=7, but since a and b are integers and the setup must be interpreted in the natural-number gcd/lcm context, the reduced relation is equivalently obtained by the standard identity gcd(m,n)·lcm(m,n)=|mn|, giving 6·126 = |mn| = 36|ab|, hence |ab|=21. Taking positive representatives yields ab=21.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"gcd-lcm product formula\",\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The only positive coprime factor pairs (a,b) with ab=21 are (1,21) and (3,7), up to order.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The prime factorization of 21 is 3·7. Since a and b are coprime and their product is 21, each prime power must lie entirely in one factor, so the only possibilities are 1·21 and 3·7, up to swapping a and b.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"unique factorization\",\n        \"coprime factorization property\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"m+n ≥ 60.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From m=6a and n=6b, we have m+n = 6(a+b). For the possible pairs from the previous step, a+b is at least 10: for (1,21), a+b=22; for (3,7), a+b=10. Therefore m+n ≥ 6·10 = 60.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"arithmetic of sums\",\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 4\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"60 ≤ m + n\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization.\n\n## Previous attempt (failed)\nYour last formalization:\n{\"theorem\":{\"variables\":[{\"name\":\"m\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"n\",\"sort\":\"Int\"}],\"hypotheses\":[\"GCD(m, n) == 6\",\"LCM(m, n) == 126\"],\"goal\":\"60 <= m + n\"},\"functions\":[],\"lemmas\":[{\"name\":\"gcd_lcm_product\",\"english\":\"For nonnegative integers, gcd(a,b) * lcm(a,b) = a * b. Here we use absolute values to cover signed integers.\",\"vars\":[{\"name\":\"a\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"b\",\"sort\":\"Int\"}],\"body\":\"Implies(And(a >= 0, b >= 0), GCD(a, b) * LCM(a, b) == a * b)\"},{\"name\":\"gcd_divides\",\"english\":\"If gcd(a,b)=d then d divides both a and b.\",\"vars\":[{\"name\":\"a\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"b\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"d\",\"sort\":\"Int\"}],\"body\":\"Implies(GCD(a, b) == d, And(Exists([k], a == d * k), Exists([k], b == d * k)))\"},{\"name\":\"reduce_coprime_lcm\",\"english\":\"If m=6a and n=6b with gcd(a,b)=1 and a,b nonnegative, then lcm(m,n)=36ab.\",\"vars\":[{\"name\":\"a\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"b\",\"sort\":\"Int\"}],\"body\":\"Implies(And(a >= 0, b >= 0, GCD(a, b) == 1), LCM(6 * a, 6 * b) == 36 * a * b)\"},{\"name\":\"coprime_factor_pairs_21\",\"english\":\"Nonnegative coprime integers a,b with product 21 must satisfy a+b >= 10.\",\"vars\":[{\"name\":\"a\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"b\",\"sort\":\"Int\"}],\"body\":\"Implies(And(a >= 0, b >= 0, GCD(a, b) == 1, a * b == 21), a + b >= 10)\"},{\"name\":\"gcd6_divisibility\",\"english\":\"If gcd(m,n)=6 then m and n are multiples of 6.\",\"vars\":[{\"name\":\"m\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"n\",\"sort\":\"Int\"}],\"body\":\"Implies(GCD(m, n) == 6, And(Exists([a], m == 6 * a), Exists([b], n == 6 * b)))\"},{\"name\":\"sum_bound_from_factor_bound\",\"english\":\"If m=6a, n=6b and a+b>=10 then m+n>=60.\",\"vars\":[{\"name\":\"m\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"n\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"a\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"b\",\"sort\":\"Int\"}],\"body\":\"Implies(And(m == 6 * a, n == 6 * b, a + b >= 10), m + n >= 60)\"}],\"instantiations\":[{\"lemma\":\"gcd6_divisibility\",\"terms\":{\"m\":\"m\",\"n\":\"n\"}},{\"lemma\":\"gcd_lcm_product\",\"terms\":{\"a\":\"Abs(m)\",\"b\":\"Abs(n)\"}},{\"lemma\":\"reduce_coprime_lcm\",\"terms\":{\"a\":\"m / 6\",\"b\":\"n / 6\"}},{\"lemma\":\"coprime_factor_pairs_21\",\"terms\":{\"a\":\"m / 6\",\"b\":\"n / 6\"}},{\"lemma\":\"sum_bound_from_factor_bound\",\"terms\":{\"m\":\"m\",\"n\":\"n\",\"a\":\"m / 6\",\"b\":\"n / 6\"}}]}\n\nErrors:\n- compile error in lemma (gcd_divides): eval failed for 'Implies(GCD(a, b) == d, And(Exists([k], a == d * k), Exists([k], b == d * k)))': name 'k' is not defined\n- compile error in lemma (gcd6_divisibility): eval failed for 'Implies(GCD(m, n) == 6, And(Exists([a], m == 6 * a), Exists([b], n == 6 * b)))': name 'a' is not defined\n- compile error in instantiation (gcd6_divisibility): eval failed for 'Implies(GCD(m, n) == 6, And(Exists([a], m == 6 * a), Exists([b], n