    "content": "## Theorem: mathd_numbertheory_3\n\nTheorem: mathd_numbertheory_3\nProve: (∑ x in finset.range 10, ((x + 1)^2)) % 10 = 5\n\nGoal: (∑ x in finset.range 10, ((x + 1)^2)) % 10 = 5\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"Expand the square and use the formulas for the sums of the first ten integers and their squares; the result is divisible down to a remainder of 5 modulo 10.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Rewrite the sum over finset.range 10 as a sum from x = 0 to 9.\",\n    \"Expand (x + 1)^2 into x^2 + 2x + 1 and split the sum into three standard sums.\",\n    \"Evaluate each standard sum explicitly.\",\n    \"Combine the values to get the total sum.\",\n    \"Reduce the total modulo 10.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"∑ x in finset.range 10, ((x + 1)^2) = ∑ x in finset.range 10, (x^2) + 2 * ∑ x in finset.range 10, x + ∑ x in finset.range 10, 1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"For each x, we have (x + 1)^2 = x^2 + 2x + 1 by expansion. Summing termwise over the finite set allows the sum to be split into the sum of x^2, twice the sum of x, and the sum of 1.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"algebraic expansion\",\n        \"sum of a sum is sum of sums\",\n        \"sum of scalar multiples\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"∑ x in finset.range 10, x = 45 and ∑ x in finset.range 10, 1 = 10.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The sum over finset.range 10 is 0 + 1 + 2 + ... + 9. Its value is 45 by the standard arithmetic series formula. There are exactly 10 terms, so the sum of 1 over these terms is 10.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"formula for 0 + 1 + ... + (n-1)\",\n        \"cardinality of finset.range\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"∑ x in finset.range 10, (x^2) = 285.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the standard sum of squares 0^2 + 1^2 + ... + 9^2, which equals 285.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"formula for sum of squares\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"∑ x in finset.range 10, ((x + 1)^2) = 400.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Substituting the values from the previous steps gives 285 + 2·45 + 10 = 400.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"400 % 10 = 5 is false; instead, 400 % 10 = 0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since 400 is divisible by 10, its remainder upon division by 10 is 0.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of modulo\",\n        \"divisibility\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"(∑ x in finset.range 10, ((x + 1)^2)) % 10 = 0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By the previous step, the sum is 400, and 400 mod 10 is 0.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"step 5\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"0\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
